node.text: Robotic exoskeletons have captivated us for years. They are major tropes in sci-fi movies and video games, and in real-life engineers have been working on them since the 1900s. San Francisco's Roam Robotics has entered into this space, and Brent Rose tries his hand at stress testing their latest military leg brace.

node.title: Stress Testing a Real-Life Military Exoskeleton

node.text: The 2021 Apple iMac is an all-in-one desktop that is powerful, yet pretty. It's lightweight and colorful, and once you plug it in you are ready to go. Tap the link in our bio to read the full review.

node.title: Apple's Colorful New iMac Pairs Beauty With Brawn

node.text: How much power do users have to influence the ways tech companies govern their platforms? This week, prominent Twitch and Reddit users separately coordinated two platform-shaking actions with the goal of making the digital spaces they work and play in safer. In the latter case, at least, it appears they've already seen results. Read more about how these protests might just be the beginning at the link in the bio.

node.text:
Frames from a camera that spent three moonless nights under the stars in the village of Magyaregres, Hungary create this composite night skyscape. They were recorded during August 11-13 while planet Earth was sweeping through the dusty trail of comet Swift-Tuttle. The radiant effect is due only to perspective, as the parallel tracks appear to converge in the distance against the starry sky.
